  "prompt": "Why did the government of India introduced a 2000 rupee note instead of a new 1000 rupee note?",
  "response": "The Indian government introduced the \u20b92000 rupee note in November 2016 as part of its demonetization policy, which aimed to curb black money, counterfeit currency, and corruption. Here are the key reasons why the \u20b92000 note was introduced instead of a new \u20b91000 note:\n\n1. **Quick Currency Replacement**: Demonetization involved the sudden withdrawal of \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes, which constituted a significant portion of the currency in circulation. Introducing a higher denomination note (\u20b92000) helped in quickly replenishing the cash supply and meeting the economy's liquidity needs.\n\n2. **Convenience in Transactions**: The \u20b92000 note reduced the physical volume of cash required for large transactions, making it more convenient for businesses and individuals to handle money.\n\n3. **Counterfeit Deterrence**: The new \u20b92000 note was designed with advanced security features to make counterfeiting more difficult, aligning with the government's goal of reducing fake currency in the economy.\n\n4. **Psychological Impact**: Introducing a higher denomination note also had a psychological effect, signaling a significant shift in the monetary system and reinforcing the message of economic reform.\n\n5. **Transition to Lower Denominations**: Over time, the government aimed to reduce reliance on high-denomination notes. The \u20b92000 note was seen as a temporary measure to ease the transition, while the focus remained on promoting digital transactions and lower-denomination notes.\n\n6. **Strategic Planning**: The introduction of the \u20b92000 note was part of a broader strategy to phase out the old \u20b9500 and \u20b91000 notes, which were perceived to be heavily used in illegal activities.\n\nHowever, the \u20b92000 note has since been gradually phased out, with the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) focusing on lower-denomination notes and digital payments to promote transparency and financial inclusion.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
